\begin_layout Standard
Genomic prediction was performed using marker subsets representing 5% to 100% of the total 4,641 SNPs.
 Predictive ability,
 assessed by the Pearson correlation between observed phenotypes and genomic estimated breeding values (GEBVs),
 varied by trait and marker density (see Figure S4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general,
 predictive ability increased rapidly with marker density up to ~40–50% of the total set,
 after which gains plateaued—
indicating diminishing returns.
 This pattern held across most color traits and LCH components (Hue,
 Chroma,
 Lightness),
 suggesting that a moderate number of well-distributed,
 informative SNPs can achieve predictive performance comparable to that of the full marker set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
